  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT251-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">piriviṭait tōḻi “paruvam aṉṟu paṭṭatu vampu” eṉṟu vaṟpuṟuttiyatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">The confidante encouraging [with the words] “that isn't
          the season; it has happened out of time”, in the time of separation. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT251">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l>maṭava vāḻi maññai yāyiṉaṅ</l>
          <l>kāla māri peyteṉa vataṉeti</l>
          <l>rālalu māliṉa piṭavum pūttaṉa</l>
          <l>kāraṉ ṟikuḷai tīrkaniṉ paṭarē</l>
          <l>kaḻinta mārik koḻinta paḻanīr</l>
          <l>putunīr koḷīiya vukuttaru</l>
          <l>notumal vāṉattu muḻaṅkukural kēṭṭē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Ignorant they [are], oh [friend], <note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vāḻi</term> may
            either be read as the prelude to a vocative not actually in the text, that is, as a kind
            of address, and then it probably has to be completed by tōḻi. Or it can be taken
            literally as a benediction of the foolish peacocks ("may you live"), but this would not
            make much sense in the context.</note> the peacocks in choice groups,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">hearing the thundering voice of the indifferent sky</l>
          <l rend="indent4">which sheds, in order to take in new water,</l>
          <l rend="indent4">the old water that stayed behind from passed showers.</l>
          <l rend="indent2">In the face of that, because a timely shower has rained,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">peyteṉa ataṉetir</term> : this is syntactically
            tricky. It might be explained as a transitional passage in the formation of the causal <term xml:lang="ta">viṉaiyeccam </term> (absolutive + <term xml:lang="ta">eṉa </term> =
            "because"). Taken in this way the sentence here would be slightly redundant: "in the
            face of that, because showers have rained". Taken, however, as an embedded direct speech
            the <term xml:lang="ta">peytu</term> would have to be taken not as an absolutive, but as
            a n.sg. p.a.: At [the thought] that: 'a timely shower has rained' (For a parallel cf. KT
            207.7: ceṉṟu eṉa kēṭṭa). This solution has the advantage that it can explain <term xml:lang="ta">ataṉetir</term> as a conjunction used by the speaker to distance
            herself from the contents of the <term xml:lang="ta">eṉa </term> clause, since she wants
            to ascertain that in fact the rain has not come in time.</note>
          </l>
          <l>they have danced [their] dance</l>
          <l rend="indent8">and the Piṭavu plants have begun to flower.</l>
          <l>It is not the rainy season, friend, may your affliction end.</l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="6b">
            <l>which sheds, so that one takes <note place="foot">For a possible parallel of <term xml:lang="ta">koḷ</term> in the sense of "to take for" (= "to mistake for") cf. KT
              127.1.</note> it for new water,</l>
          </lg>
        </lg>
      </div>
